	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320004_01.jpg"/>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_rozentsvayg_leyb">Rozentsvayg Leyb</persName>, office worker</p>
			<p>Age: 25 years, former address: <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Muranów 8</placeName></p>
			<p>Left <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName> on the <date when="1939-10-14">14th October
					1939</date></p>

			<p>Testimony number 4</p>

			<p>The Jewish population was preparing for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term>.
				Groups were formed, people worked in the trenches, all tasks and injunctions were accomplished zealously. On the night of <date
					when="1939-09-06">6th September</date> there was an alert, our whole area was mobilised to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> in the trenches on <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Bielany</placeName>. At the gathering place anarchy reigned, there was no leader;
				several trams without conductors were parked there. When we got to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html"
					>Bielany</placeName>, we were sent back – all of us, those who came with shovels or without. We heard loud shooting. People
				started to run in all directions. Thousands of people left <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html"
					>Warsaw</placeName> at that time, by the road to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/764679/minsk-mazowiecki.html">Minsk
					Mazowiecki</placeName> or to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html">Lublin</placeName>.</p>

			<p>I met a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">policeman</term> that morning (on the <date
					when="1939-09-07">7th [of September]</date>). He said that they [=the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">police</term>] were retreating together with the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">army</term> by the road to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html">Lublin</placeName> and that the young people should also come with them. So I set
				off on the road to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html">Lublin</placeName>.</p>

			<p>On the road stretched masses of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldiers</term> and
				civilians. The whole road was crowded with people. The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term> planes did not let
				them rest, but bombed constantly. People were constantly hiding, victims were lying on the road: <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldiers</term>, civilians, horses. There was nothing
				to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">eat</term>. From the field we would grab <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">carrots</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">beetroot</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">tomatoes</term>; it was also hard to find water, the
				wells were already empty.</p>

			<p>Near <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/759852/ryki.html">Ryki</placeName>, troops were camped, with a high-ranking officer. He
				was sending the people back: an order from <persName ref="#ehri_et_starzynski_stefan">Starzyński</persName>, we were to go back to
				defend <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName>. He only let pass a certain category of
				conscripts. Therefore a lot of civilians returned, and so did I.</p>

			<p><pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320004_02.jpg"/></p>
			<p>On the way back there was heavy bombing, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/768807/kolbiel.html">Kołbiel</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/764679/minsk-mazowiecki.html">Minsk Mazowiecki</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/772339/garwolin.html">Garwolin</placeName> were burning. It was impossible to get through. We kept on
				going to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/774641/celestynow.html">Celestynów</placeName>-<placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/762788/otwock.html">Otwock</placeName>. There we got a kilo of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>. In <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/762788/otwock.html">Otwock</placeName> only a few places suffered damages. From there we took the
				local <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-940" type="subject">train</term> to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756092/wawer.html">Wawer</placeName>, where the planes were constantly overhead. Masses of people lay
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead</term> or wounded, there was no place to
				hide.</p>

			<p><placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756092/wawer.html">Wawer</placeName>. We went into a house that was standing open, a small
				wooden house. There we stayed the whole day Sunday, <date when="1939-09-10">10th September</date>. In the evening, continued toward
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName>. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead</term> lay on the road, people and horses. There
				were lost helmets, articles of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothing</term>. All
				of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8425897/olszynka-grochowska.html">Grochowska</placeName> was burning, fallen telegraph
				poles, bomb craters.</p>

			<p>In <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/761318/praga.html">Praga</placeName>, cannon-fire, shrapnel, every few minutes we had to
				take shelter in a doorway. <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/761318/praga.html">Praga</placeName> was already unrecognizable,
				particularly around the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/761318/praga.html">Przem.[ienienia] Pańskiego</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">hospital</term>, near the church, on the right,
				already we could not cross Kierbedź bridge, which was badly damaged. I reached <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName> only in the evening.</p>

			<p>The <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName> streets were empty, unrecognizable. On <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Nalewki- Franciszkańska</placeName> they were grabbing Jews for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> details, for the trenches. In the <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term> districts, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943"
					type="subject">work</term> was voluntary, they picked up people in the streets only in the Jewish district, despite the fact that
				the Jewish professional or party organizations (<orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-1172"
					>Bundists</orgName>, Skifists, even in uniform), and Jews with [traditional] Jewish hats, were going to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> in organized groups with shovels.</p>

			<p>At <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Senatorska Street 29</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Luxenburg Gallery</placeName>, there was a bureau to recruit volunteers, which
				was besieged by Jews. Some <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Poles</term> even expressed their displeasure that there were too
				many Jews. I myself <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> with a group of
				Jewish <pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320004_03.jpg"/> transport <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943"
					type="subject">workers</term>, we sang revolutionary songs, no one could expect that in a few days all the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> would be for nothing.</p>

			<p>My neighborhood had suffered badly from the bombing. In my house, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html"
					>Muranowska 6-8</placeName>, the adjoining wall had completely collapsed, so we had to move out. We found a place at <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Prosta 14</placeName>, in the high school. It had a shelter, where there were
				already <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-304" type="subject">refugees</term> from <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/752967/zyrardow.html">Żyrardów</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/754351/zabki.html">Ząbki</placeName>, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/775820/blonie.html"
					>Błonie</placeName> and others. There were whole <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject"
					>families</term> with <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>. They had
				been given the cellars of the school. The bombings took place in the morning and evening, every day another district was hit. There
				was also a lot of shrapnel, as the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> got closer to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName>. The planes threw out appeals telling us to surrender. In the
				Jewish neighborhood, the hardest hit streets were <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Stawki</placeName>,
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Niska</placeName>, and parts of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Miła</placeName>. Also badly hit were <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Nalewki</placeName> and <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Franciszkańska</placeName>. The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans"
					>Germans</term> heavily bombed the churches on <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Leszno</placeName>,
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Grzybów</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Zbawiciela Square</placeName> and others. The worst damage was in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Wola</placeName>, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html"
					>Mokotów</placeName> and <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Marymont</placeName>. The hardest hit of all
				were the houses with <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">military</term> points.</p>

			<p>The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> entered <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html"
					>Warsaw</placeName> on <date when="1939-10-02">2nd</date> and <date when="1939-10-03">3rd October</date>. First they opened <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup kitchens</term> to feed the population, who
				rushed to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">kitchens</term>. A crowd of 50 000
				gathered on <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Broni Square</placeName>, standing in 4 rows which extended
				the whole length of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Bonifraterska</placeName>. From 4 tables with 4 large
				vats, the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> distributed <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>, and they filmed it all from a truck and
				played <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">military</term> marches. Someone greeted the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldiers</term> in Polish.They made no
				distinction between non-Jews and Jews, even those wearing Hasidic <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836"
					type="subject">dress</term>.</p>

			<p>But in the following days there began to be a difference between Jews and non-Jews. For clearing the rubble they rounded up only Jews
				in the Jewish quarters. In the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term> quarters this was not done. By this time there
				was no water, no electricity ; <pb n="4" facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320004_04.jpg"/> Jews had to go for water to the <placeName
					ref="#ehri_et_vistula">Vistula</placeName> or to the wells, and already some <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Poles</term>
				were starting to say things like: <persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000185">Hitler</persName>'s here
				already, he'll soon be getting even with the Jews.</p>

			<p>By the <placeName ref="#ehri_et_vistula">Vistula</placeName>, I once saw the following: A young Gentile grabbed a large pitcher of
				water that an elderly Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term> was
				carrying and poured it all out. This was already quite a distance from the river. An older <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">man</term>, also a Gentile, reacted like this: What
				kind of a person are you, to do this in such a time. What would you do if someone did that to you?</p>

			<p>Life was very hard. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">Bread</term> was impossible to
				find. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">Potatoes</term> cost 3 złoty a kilo and were
				also hard to find. Brave young <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term> went out
				to the fields, dug up <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potatoes</term> and sold them.
				No transportation existed. I saw the following scene: A Gentile came up to a Jewish boy to buy cigarettes. He asked the price, then
				quickly called over a <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldier</term>, who took all the cigarettes away
				from the boy and tossed them to the crowd. The Gentiles caught them. Another scene: a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">policeman</term> came up to woman selling <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">herring</term> and asked the price. Then he took it
				all and gave it out to the crowd.</p>

			<p>The shops were completely closed. All commerce was in the streets. Before the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>
				arrived there was a lot of robbery: <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldiers</term> would steal, as well as the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-119" type="subject">criminals</term> who had been let out of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-669" type="subject">jail</term>. There were whole gangs. We posted guards
				by the gates. Some firms, however, themselves distributed their goods to the population, just so it wouldn’t fall into the hands of
				the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>.</p>

			<p><placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName> under the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans"
					>Germans</term>: <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Nowolipki</placeName> from <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Zamenhof</placeName> to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Karmelicka</placeName> was cleared of all Jews. Within the space of one or two
				hours all Jews had to leave their homes. The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> cleaned up the street, there
				was no passage off <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Nowolipki</placeName>.</p>

			<p>The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> would grab Jews for work details and also make fun of them. I myself saw
				this scene: they asked an elderly Jew to clean the pavement with his beard. <pb n="5" facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320004_05.jpg"/> The Jew bent
				down and began wiping with his hands and they didn’t bother him any more. In many cases they forced people to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> but there were no shovels, no tools, and
				they had to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> with their bare hands.</p>

			<p>The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term> population stood in line to get <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>, mainly in the <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term> neighborhoods. They would throw Jews off the line. If a Jew refused to leave they
				would call over a <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">policeman</term> and point to him:</p>
			<p>Jude! Jude! and they would throw him out. Particularly good at these <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-329"
					type="subject">anti-Semitic</term> acts were the volunteer members of the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">militia</term>: One of these took hold of a Jew by
				his lapel and pulled him off the line. <q>For Jews there's no <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
						type="subject">bread</term>!</q> For some Gentiles a little business sprang up – to sell loaves of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> to Jews at exorbitant prices.</p>

			<p>A new means of livelihood became available for Jews also during the water shortage: carrying water on pushcarts; there were also Jews
				who would stand in line (for a fee).</p>

			<p>Until the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> entered <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html"
					>Warsaw</placeName>, a four-page edition of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-723" type="subject"
					>Folkstsaytung</term> came out every day; once they were there, Yiddish newspapers were no longer available. There was only <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1069" type="subject">Kurier Poranny</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1069" type="subject">Dziennik Ludowy</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1069" type="subject">Kurier Warszawski</term>, but they all carried
				exactly the same contents.</p>

			<p>There were 2 appeals from <persName ref="#ehri_et_starzynski_stefan">Starzyński</persName> to the population. 12 guarantors were
				appointed, to be responsible for keeping the peace in the city. Among them were <persName ref="#ehri_et_zygielbojm_szmul">Szmul
					Zygielbojm</persName> (Artur), <persName ref="#ehri_et_gepner_abraham">Gepner</persName>, <persName ref="#ehri_et_lubomirski"
					>Count Lubomirski</persName>, <persName ref="#ehri_et_zaremba">Zaremba</persName>, etc.</p>

			<p>After a week and a half under the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> I decided to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escape</term>; I expected that later things would
				become worse, that there would be special <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-641" type="subject"
					>persecutions</term> for the younger generation. The city made a terrifying impression after the bombing.</p>

			<p>I left for <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Falenica</placeName> in order to continue on from there. In
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Falenica</placeName> the entire <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Handlowa Street</placeName> had been burned. In <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Falenica</placeName> the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans"
					>Germans</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> a number <pb n="6"
					facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320004_06.jpg"/> of Jews, supposedly taking them to a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoners</term>' <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term>, but <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shooting</term> them on the way.</p>

			<p>As a former patient of the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Medem Sanatorium</placeName>, I wanted to have a
				look at the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Miedzeszyn</placeName>. When I reached the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term> I found no one there. So I went in
				to see the guardian <persName ref="#ehri_et_maksimenko">Maksimenko</persName> and he described to me in tears the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">plundering</term> of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term>: there were <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldiers</term> in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term> and they robbed the place together
				with the civilian population. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldiers</term>
				simply let the civilians in and whoever wanted to could steal whatever they wanted, and they took everything, beds, mattresses,
				everything. With tears, <persName ref="#ehri_et_maksimenko">Maksimenko</persName> explained: All he could do was to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-217" type="subject">kill himself</term>, for it was his responsibility and
				he was unable to prevent the destruction. As we entered the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282"
					type="subject">sanatorium</term> we were struck by a terrible smell. A great number of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead</term> horses were buried here. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term> buildings were standing but
				everything was in disorder, everything thrown about, the rooms empty, even the door handles had been stolen. In the kitchen the
				cooking pots had been taken. <persName ref="#ehri_et_maksimenko">Maksimenko</persName> said: I know where all these things are. If the
				directors of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term> would come we
				could get them back.</p>

			<p>When I came back a second time I found 9 staff members, technical and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-286" type="subject">medical personnel</term>: they decided to set up a
				collective and began to put the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term> in
				order. I found them <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">working</term> with rakes and
				brooms. We prepared a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">lunch</term> together, not in
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term>, but at the home of a friend
				who <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term> and lived nearby. I never entered
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">sanatorium</term> again.</p>

			<p>The next day, the <date when="1939-10-17">17</date>/<date when="1939-10-18">18th October</date>, I continued on my way, through
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/764679/minsk-mazowiecki.html">Minsk-Maz.[owiecki]</placeName>, to the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/697134/pivdennyy-buh.html">Bug River</placeName>. In <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/764679/minsk-mazowiecki.html">Minsk</placeName>, for the first time I had some <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>. There were a lot of <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldiers</term>. I also heard there was a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoners</term>' <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term> there, with many Jews, even civilians. The
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term> was in the open air.</p>

			<p><pb n="7" facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320004_07.jpg"/></p>
			<p>From <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/764679/minsk-mazowiecki.html">Minsk</placeName> I left for <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/769738/kaluszyn.html">Kaluszyn</placeName>. Nothing was left of the entire town. All that remained
				was bits of walls sticking up, but the church was still there. Those who had hidden in the church survived. The <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Poles</term> saw this as a miracle. They estimated the number of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/769738/kaluszyn.html">Kaluszyn</placeName> to be 900, most of them Jews. Everyone told me: They had
				never seen such destruction, a whole town wiped out!</p>

			<p>From <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/769738/kaluszyn.html">Kaluszyn</placeName> I went to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/759412/siedlce.html">Siedlce</placeName>. While I was there they were rounding up Jews in the street
				for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> details. A large part of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/759412/siedlce.html">Siedlce</placeName> was burned down. We were able to get <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>. The Jews complained that the Bolsheviks
				had retreated, for they had already been close to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/759412/siedlce.html"
				>Siedlce</placeName>.</p>

			<p>Then I headed for <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/764407/mordy.html">Mordy</placeName>. There too they were taking Jews for
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">labor</term>. I heard about <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756046/wegrow.html">Węgrów</placeName>: they <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">stabbed</term> the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-735" type="subject">rabbi</term> with a knife. Many Jews were assembled in
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-758" type="subject">synagogue</term> and the <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> opened fire on the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-758" type="subject">synagogue</term>. The Jews threw themselves on the
				ground and the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> kept them there all day under threat of being <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term>. No one was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">killed</term>, only wounded. They also related: From
				those who reached the Bug the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> took everything: rings, furs, and distributed
				it all to the Christian population. From <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/764407/mordy.html">Mordy</placeName> I went to the
				Bug, using back roads, then crossed the river with a small boat near <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/772959/drohiczyn.html"
					>Drohiczyn</placeName>. At night, on the other side I met <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_soviets">Soviet</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldiers</term>, who gave me <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">dinner</term> and a place to sleep. All the sites that
				the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_soviets">Soviets</term> occupied after the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans"
					>Germans</term> were totally <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject"
				>plundered</term>.</p>
